{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a16bf1dc-6c0f-495c-9c2b-27d82b465e46","content":"Here's the correct attribute for each framework:\n\n| Framework | Attribute |\n|-----------|-----------|\n| **MSTest** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **xUnit** | `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` or `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]` |\n| **NUnit** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **TUnit** | `[Skip(\"reason\")]` |\n\n**Examples:**\n\n```csharp\n// MSTest\n[TestMethod]\n[Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyMsTest() { }\n\n// xUnit\n[Fact(Skip = \"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyXunitTest() { }\n\n// NUnit\n[Test]\n[Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyNunitTest() { }\n\n// TUnit\n[Test]\n[Skip(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic Task MyTunitTest() => Task.CompletedTask;\n```\n\n> **Note:** In xUnit, `Skip` is a property on `[Fact]`/`[Theory]`, not a separate attribute. In the other three frameworks it's a standalone attribute placed alongside the test method attribute.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bfb03078-7f55-40cc-8a97-ff3b830a0819","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about test-skipping attributes across four .NET test frameworks. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without tools.","outputTokens":333,"requestId":"9825:19EA9:1C1112:248E65:69FFDC79"},"id":"b44f59df-e89b-47c1-a36d-57f97646b3ce","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:16:48.072Z","parentId":"dc288f51-4815-4995-9057-eaa8b586c0b9"}
